\subsection*{Q2: Projection-aware partial identification with sparse histories}

\paragraph{Axes.}
DGP: \texttt{ {{ dgpName }} }; Baseline: \texttt{ {{ baselineName }} };
Assignment: \texttt{ {{ assignmentName }} } (sparse-support, with at least
one history missing); Regression: \texttt{ {{ regressionName }} };
Target: \texttt{ {{ targetName }} }.

\paragraph{Setup.}
$p = 1$, binary treatment, histories $H_{it} \in \{00, 01, 10, 11\}$, no
anticipation, untreated baseline. Only the support $S = \{00, 01, 11\}$
has positive probability (history $10$ is never observed). Outcomes are
bounded: $Y_{it}(h) \in [L, U]$ for every $h$.

\paragraph{Tasks.}
\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=2em]
  \item Define the observed-support response vector $m_S$ and the missing
        component $m(10)$.
  \item Saturated-history regression with $00$ omitted: state the rank
        condition and identify which coefficients are defined.
  \item Explain how a point-identified saturated-history coefficient differs
        from a causal contrast that assigns nonzero formal weight to the
        missing history $10$.
  \item Sharp bounds for any linear estimand
        $\theta = \sum_{h} a_h m(h)$ using only $m(10) \in [L, U]$;
        specialize to the missing-history contrast $m(10) - m(11)$.
  \item State a theorem separating the identified projection part and the
        unidentified extrapolation part.
  \item Step-by-step proof; sharpness via two response surfaces agreeing
        on observed histories but disagreeing on $m(10)$.
  \item Formalization checklist.
\end{enumerate}
